T hough under the ius civile neither adrogatornor adrogatus could be sued for debts incurred by the latter before his capitis deminutio, the debts remained as obligationes naturales, Dig. 4. 5. a. 2, and the praetor granted actiones utiles against adrogatus himself (Gaius iii. 84) under the fiction that he was still sui iuris: ‘rescissa capitis deminutione, id est [actio] in qua tingitur capite deminutus non esse' Gaius iv. 38. This was a genuine in integrum restitutio of the creditors: ‘integri restitutionem praetor tribuit ex his causis quae per. . . status permutationem gesta esse dicuntur' l'aul. sent. rec. 1. 7. 2.
